text:
If you need help sleeping, then I have at least three recommendations, though it'll take a few days for it to take effect.

1. As soon as you put your phone or some other electronic device down, never touch it again until you wake up and get ready for work. The bright lights strain your eyes and trick your brain into thinking it's still daytime.

2. Set a hard deadline for when you go to bed. For example, if you want to go to bed at 11 PM, you must stick with that time no matter what. Do this every day and your body will prepare itself for sleep.

3. There's a sleeping technique allegedly used by military guys where you focus on each individual part of your body for twenty seconds. You start from the top of your head and mentally make your way down to your toes. Supposedly if you do it right, this can help you fall asleep within two minutes in any position.

Hopefully this helps! As long as you stick with it, you should be getting a good night's sleep again within a week.

text:
(Guess who missed the second half of last night's stream cause he found out he's developed, of all things, a SHRIMP allergy? It's not too bad, so I was fine, but I took some meds that knocked me out midstream. So just a little add on about that stream first: I'm really glad you enjoyed Subnautica way more than you thought you would Gura! I heard you mention it was scary a few times too, just you wait for the DEEEEEEEP OCEAN!)

Anyway, Gura, if I can be kinda serious for a minute? I try to avoid ever seriously telling you to do anything, cause none of us personally know you and your life, and it's not something we have any right to do. But please always make sure to focus on your own health first. You've always been one to tell us how you're feeling (and we really do appreciate it) but hearing you mention worrying about your memory and needing food on top of having sleep problems, and getting super hot in your stream room you spend so much time in every day (AND you didn't eat your veggies today apparently!) does actually sound a little concerning.

I don't want to overreact, or invite others to do the same, because we still only have the barest idea how you're feeling, and I don't want you to feel like you have to stop telling us how you're doing. But if you're concerned about parts of your health like those, please make sure to address them first before worrying about streaming. If you need to cancel or shorten some streams so you can fix your sleep schedule, please do; if you need to take a break for a few minutes to get some food, PLEASE do (we enjoy hearing shark nomming noises anyway). And Gura, oh my lord, if you're overheating PLEASE use a fan of some sort, even if we end up hearing it on stream. It's funny and sweet you're that concerned about the stream quality, but also a little scary. We know you work hard for us, and we dearly appreciate it and would never doubt that fact; but we also cherish the heck out of you, and want you to do whatever you need to to stay healthy, comfortable, and HERE. Please, Gura.

(And PLEASE look into if there's some kind of medication or anything to help you sleep. That's a super selfish request, but you really need rest...)

Also, as far as stream schedules go, I do appreciate them and use them to know when to be around for streams, but it's okay if you wanna just play it by ear. It's helpful already that you start around the same time every stream! Maybe you could try to schedule what days you'll be streaming, but not necessarily what, ahead of time? Either way, Gura, you don't need to stress yourself out trying to plan everything ahead of time. It's really okay. And if you can't think of any games you wanna play, any kind of stream is welcome! Surprise karaoke, or non-members watchalongs, drawing streams, chatting streams...anything is great.

That's obviously more than enough of me being super serious and dumping words into this comment though. Looking forward to the member's stream! Love you, little shark. Remember to smile!
